2 Factors

2.1 Introduction

  • A factor variable is Rs way to differentiate categorical data, i.e., a variable where each observational/experimental unit belongs to one and only one group, category, or level out of a set of groups, categories, or levels.
  • Being designated as a factor allows R to provide special treatment to the data
    • Hair Color could be a factor with levels: Auburn, Red, Brown, Black, Blonde,
    • City sizes: Small, Medium, Large, or Megalopolis
    • Major: Data Science, Mathematics, Statistics, or Other
  • Factors may have words as labels for the levels but they are different from a character variable such as Brown or Small:
    1. Factors have a fixed (usually small) number of levels (possible values)
      • A character variable, e.g., City_name, can have many different values.
    2. Factors have a default ordering of the levels
      • Character variables are only ordered through alpha-numeric sequencing
      • Note the Default ordering for factors in R is alpha-numeric but you can change it to whatever makes sense for the problem
      • Ordering is useful when determining the order to plot something.

2.2 Example

  • Consider the following data frame for average highs in DC for each month.

    library(tidyverse)
dcclimate <- tribble(~month, ~avehigh,
                     ##----/---------
                     "Jan",  43.4,
                     "Feb",  47.1,
                     "Mar",  55.9,
                     "Apr",  66.6,
                     "May",  75.4,
                     "Jul",  88.4,
                     "Aux",  86.5,
                     "Sep",  79.5,
                     "Oct",  68.4,
                     "Nov",  57.9,
                     "Dec",  46.8)
head(dcclimate)
    ## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   month avehigh
##   <chr>   <dbl>
## 1 Jan      43.4
## 2 Feb      47.1
## 3 Mar      55.9
## 4 Apr      66.6
## 5 May      75.4
## 6 Jul      88.4

  • Notice Month is a character variable. What happens when we plot the data?

    ggplot(dcclimate, aes(x = month, y = avehigh)) +
  geom_col()

  • The months are not in alphabetical, not calendar, order - A months came first

  • Its hard to see the weather for June is missing

  • The 3-letter abbreviation for August is incorrect.

  • Factors (and forcats) can help us address all of these issues.

2.3 Factors have some nuances as they have two different representations

  • When we look at the data, we see the labels of the levels be they words or numbers

    • Use levels(factor_var) to access the labels and the order of the levels

  • R actually stores factors as integers from 1, 2, number of levels

    • Wse as.numeric(factor_var) to access the stored integer values

  • Be careful when working with factor data as results may be counter-intuitive at first.

  • Example: Assume an experimental treatment has levels 2, 15, 32, and 51

    x  <- c("51", "32", "15", "2", "32")
xf <- factor(x)
class(x)
    ## [1] "character"
    as.numeric(x)
    ## [1] 51 32 15  2 32
    as.numeric(xf)
    ## [1] 4 3 1 2 3
    class(xf)
    ## [1] "factor"
    typeof(xf)
    ## [1] "integer"

    • Converting a character variable to a factor

      as.numeric("Hello")
      ## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
      ## [1] NA
      as.numeric(factor("Hello"))
      ## [1] 1

    • Combining factors with c() combines the integer representations, not the levels

      fac1 <- factor(c("x1", "x2", "x3", "X5"))
fac2 <- factor(c("y1", "y2", "y3"))
c(levels(fac1),levels(fac2))
      ## [1] "x1" "x2" "x3" "X5" "y1" "y2" "y3"
      c(fac1, fac2)
      ## [1] 1 2 3 4 1 2 3

2.4 Converting Factor Variables with Numbers as Levels to Numeric Variables

  • Sometimes data can have numbers coded as a factor (as in xf above), but you want to work with the actual numbers (as they have mathematical relationships)

  • When you are sure all levels of a factor variable are numeric, you can convert the values of a factor variable to be numeric.

  • Does the following work?

    xf
    ## [1] 51 32 15 2  32
## Levels: 15 2 32 51
    levels(xf)
    ## [1] "15" "2"  "32" "51"
    parse_number(levels(xf)) 
    ## [1] 15  2 32 51

  • No, it just converts the 4 levels but not the whole vector of 5 observations

  • Consider using the integer representation from as.numeric() inside select brackets

    • Take advantage of recycling

      xf
      ## [1] 51 32 15 2  32
## Levels: 15 2 32 51
      as.numeric(xf)
      ## [1] 4 3 1 2 3
      xf[xf]
      ## [1] 2  15 51 32 15
## Levels: 15 2 32 51
      levels(xf)
      ## [1] "15" "2"  "32" "51"
      levels(xf)[xf]
      ## [1] "51" "32" "15" "2"  "32"
      class(levels(xf)[xf])
      ## [1] "character"

    • This creates a vector of characters for the numerics for all the observations in the original variable

    • The final step is parse the vector of characters to convert to numeric

  • You can do the entire conversion in one step as follows:

    parse_number(levels(xf)[xf])
    ## [1] 51 32 15  2 32
    # to confirm
class(parse_number(levels(xf)[xf]))
    ## [1] "numeric"

3 Creating Factors

3.1 readr and base R have functions to create factor variables

  • Use parse_factor() (readr) or factor() (base R) to create a factor variable

  • parse_factor() returns better warnings, so use it whenever possible.

  • Example where we try to set the levels to the standard abbreviations in calendar order

    monthvec <- c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", 
              "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec")

# or consider using month.abb to eliminate typos...
#  as it's a built-in constant for the month abbreviations
month.abb
    ##  [1] "Jan" "Feb" "Mar" "Apr" "May" "Jun" "Jul" "Aug" "Sep" "Oct" "Nov" "Dec"
    monthvec <- month.abb 

dcclimate %>%
  mutate(monthfc = factor(month, levels = monthvec)) ->
  dcclimate

dcclimate %>%
  mutate(monthfc2 = parse_factor(month, levels = monthvec)) ->
  dcclimate
    ## Warning: 1 parsing failure.
## row col           expected actual
##   7  -- value in level set    Aux
    dcclimate$monthfc
    ##  [1] Jan  Feb  Mar  Apr  May  Jul  <NA> Sep  Oct  Nov  Dec 
## Levels: Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec
    as.integer(dcclimate$monthfc)
    ##  [1]  1  2  3  4  5  7 NA  9 10 11 12
    dcclimate$monthfc2
    ##  [1] Jan  Feb  Mar  Apr  May  Jul  <NA> Sep  Oct  Nov  Dec 
## attr(,"problems")
## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##     row   col expected           actual
##   <int> <int> <chr>              <chr> 
## 1     7    NA value in level set Aux   
## Levels: Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec
    as.integer(dcclimate$monthfc2)
    ##  [1]  1  2  3  4  5  7 NA  9 10 11 12

3.2 Working with factor levels and their order

  • If you do not specify the levels argument, R will assume the levels are the unique values of the vector.

    • factor() takes the order of the levels to be the same order returned by sort().
    • parse_factor() takes the order of the levels to be the same order as the order of the values as introduced.

  • Example: Notice the different order of the levels

    x <- c("A", "string", "vector", "is", "a", "string", "vector")
factor(x)
    ## [1] A      string vector is     a      string vector
## Levels: a A is string vector
    sort(unique(x))
    ## [1] "a"      "A"      "is"     "string" "vector"
    parse_factor(x)
    ## [1] A      string vector is     a      string vector
## Levels: A string vector is a

  • You can always see the levels of a factor (and their order) using the levels() function

    levels(dcclimate$monthfc)
    ##  [1] "Jan" "Feb" "Mar" "Apr" "May" "Jun" "Jul" "Aug" "Sep" "Oct" "Nov" "Dec"

  • Other options are the fct_unique() and fct_count() functions from the forcats package.

    fct_unique(dcclimate$monthfc)
    ##  [1] Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec
## Levels: Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec
    fct_count(dcclimate$monthfc)
    ## # A tibble: 13 x 2
##    f         n
##    <fct> <int>
##  1 Jan       1
##  2 Feb       1
##  3 Mar       1
##  4 Apr       1
##  5 May       1
##  6 Jun       0
##  7 Jul       1
##  8 Aug       0
##  9 Sep       1
## 10 Oct       1
## 11 Nov       1
## 12 Dec       1
## 13 <NA>      1

  • You can count the number of levels with nlevels().

    nlevels(dcclimate$monthfc)
    ## [1] 12

  • A factor variables level order sets the order of the labels used by the ggplot aesthetic mapping.

    • NAs are last

      ggplot(dcclimate, aes(x = monthfc, y = avehigh)) +
  geom_col()

  • We can include missing levels by using the drop = FALSE argument in the appropriate scale call:

    ggplot(dcclimate, aes(x = monthfc, y = avehigh)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_x_discrete(drop = FALSE)

4 The tidyverse forcats Package

  • The forcats package has functions to make it easier to manipulate factors:
    • Changing the order of the levels of a factor variable.
    • Changing the levels of a factor variable.
    • It also has a few other helper functions for factors.
  • All forcats functions begin with fct_. So you can type fct_ then use tab-completion to scroll through the possible functions.

4.1 Changing the Order of the Levels

  • Consider the subset of the data from the General Social Survey stored in the gss_cat data set in forcats.

    data(gss_cat)
glimpse(gss_cat)
    ## Rows: 21,483
## Columns: 9
## $ year    <int> 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2000, 2
## $ marital <fct> Never married, Divorced, Widowed, Never married, Divorced, Ma
## $ age     <int> 26, 48, 67, 39, 25, 25, 36, 44, 44, 47, 53, 52, 52, 51, 52, 4
## $ race    <fct> White, White, White, White, White, White, White, White, White
## $ rincome <fct> $8000 to 9999, $8000 to 9999, Not applicable, Not applicable,
## $ partyid <fct> "Ind,near rep", "Not str republican", "Independent", "Ind,nea
## $ relig   <fct> Protestant, Protestant, Protestant, Orthodox-christian, None,
## $ denom   <fct> Southern baptist, Baptist-dk which, No denomination, Not appl
## $ tvhours <int> 12, NA, 2, 4, 1, NA, 3, NA, 0, 3, 2, NA, 1, NA, 1, 7, NA, 3,

  • You often want to change the order of the levels of a factor to make plots more insightful or easier to interpret.

  • Example: TV hours by Religion - default order

    gss_cat %>%
  group_by(relig) %>%
  summarize(tvhours_mean = mean(tvhours, na.rm = TRUE)) ->
  tvdat
    ## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
    ggplot(tvdat, aes(x = tvhours_mean, y = relig)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Average TV Hours") +
  ylab("Religion")

  • Use fct_reorder() (inside a mutate()) to reorder the levels of a factor based on the values of another variable. The arguments are:

    • f: The factor vector.
    • x: A numeric vector you want to use to reorder the levels (default is ascending order (desc = FALSE)).
    • fun: A function you may want to apply to x, the result of which will be used to order the levels of f.
      • default is the median

  • Lets reorder relig based on the mean of TV hours we calculated earlier

    levels(tvdat$relig)
    ##  [1] "No answer"               "Don't know"             
##  [3] "Inter-nondenominational" "Native american"        
##  [5] "Christian"               "Orthodox-christian"     
##  [7] "Moslem/islam"            "Other eastern"          
##  [9] "Hinduism"                "Buddhism"               
## [11] "Other"                   "None"                   
## [13] "Jewish"                  "Catholic"               
## [15] "Protestant"              "Not applicable"
    tvdat %>%
  mutate(relig = fct_reorder(relig, tvhours_mean)) ->
  tvdat
levels(tvdat$relig)
    ##  [1] "Other eastern"           "Hinduism"               
##  [3] "Buddhism"                "Orthodox-christian"     
##  [5] "Moslem/islam"            "Jewish"                 
##  [7] "None"                    "No answer"              
##  [9] "Other"                   "Christian"              
## [11] "Inter-nondenominational" "Catholic"               
## [13] "Protestant"              "Native american"        
## [15] "Don't know"              "Not applicable"

  • The plot now reorders the y-axis according to the new level order.

    ggplot(tvdat, aes(x = tvhours_mean, y = relig)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Average TV Hours") +
  ylab("Religion")

  • fct_rev() reverses the order of the factors.

    tvdat %>%
  mutate(relig = fct_rev(relig)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = tvhours_mean, y = relig)) +
    geom_point() +
    xlab("Average TV Hours") +
    ylab("Religion")

  • fct_relevel() allows you to move existing levels to any location you choose.

    • Note the use of integer values, e.g., 2L

    • Any levels not mentioned will be left in existing order

      ## Moves "None" to first level
fct_relevel(tvdat$relig, "None") %>%
  levels()
      ##  [1] "None"                    "Other eastern"          
##  [3] "Hinduism"                "Buddhism"               
##  [5] "Orthodox-christian"      "Moslem/islam"           
##  [7] "Jewish"                  "No answer"              
##  [9] "Other"                   "Christian"              
## [11] "Inter-nondenominational" "Catholic"               
## [13] "Protestant"              "Native american"        
## [15] "Don't know"              "Not applicable"
      ## Moves "None" to the third level
fct_relevel(tvdat$relig, "None", after = 2L) %>%
  levels()
      ##  [1] "Other eastern"           "Hinduism"               
##  [3] "None"                    "Buddhism"               
##  [5] "Orthodox-christian"      "Moslem/islam"           
##  [7] "Jewish"                  "No answer"              
##  [9] "Other"                   "Christian"              
## [11] "Inter-nondenominational" "Catholic"               
## [13] "Protestant"              "Native american"        
## [15] "Don't know"              "Not applicable"
      ## Moves "None" to the last level
fct_relevel(tvdat$relig, "None", after = nlevels(tvdat$relig)) %>%
  levels()
      ##  [1] "Other eastern"           "Hinduism"               
##  [3] "Buddhism"                "Orthodox-christian"     
##  [5] "Moslem/islam"            "Jewish"                 
##  [7] "No answer"               "Other"                  
##  [9] "Christian"               "Inter-nondenominational"
## [11] "Catholic"                "Protestant"             
## [13] "Native american"         "Don't know"             
## [15] "Not applicable"          "None"
      ## Returns a warning because "Cthulhuism" is not a level
fct_relevel(tvdat$relig, "Cthulhuism")
      ## Warning: Unknown levels in `f`: Cthulhuism
      ##  [1] No answer               Don't know              Inter-nondenominational
##  [4] Native american         Christian               Orthodox-christian     
##  [7] Moslem/islam            Other eastern           Hinduism               
## [10] Buddhism                Other                   None                   
## [13] Jewish                  Catholic                Protestant             
## 16 Levels: Other eastern Hinduism Buddhism Orthodox-christian ... Not applicable

4.2 Modify Factor Levels

  • Look at the levels of partyid in gss_cat.

    levels(gss_cat$partyid)
    ##  [1] "No answer"          "Don't know"         "Other party"       
##  [4] "Strong republican"  "Not str republican" "Ind,near rep"      
##  [7] "Independent"        "Ind,near dem"       "Not str democrat"  
## [10] "Strong democrat"

  • Use fct_recode() (inside a mutate()) to change the labels for the levels.

    • The new label level goes on the left of the equals sign. The old label level goes on the right. Think New <- Old (Just like mutate()!)

      gss_cat %>%
  mutate(partyid = fct_recode(partyid,
                              "Republican, strong"    = "Strong republican",
                              "Republican, weak"      = "Not str republican",
                              "Independent, near rep" = "Ind,near rep",
                              "Independent, near dem" = "Ind,near dem",
                              "Democrat, weak"        = "Not str democrat",
                              "Democrat, strong"      = "Strong democrat"
                              )) ->
  gss_cat
levels(gss_cat$partyid)
      ##  [1] "No answer"             "Don't know"            "Other party"          
##  [4] "Republican, strong"    "Republican, weak"      "Independent, near rep"
##  [7] "Independent"           "Independent, near dem" "Democrat, weak"       
## [10] "Democrat, strong"

4.2.1 Exercise

  • Modify the factor levels of marital to be abbreviations of their long-names. For example, Divorced can just be D

4.3 Other Useful Functions.

  • fct_c(): is the safe way to combine factor vectors.

    fc1 <- parse_factor(c("A", "B"))
fc1
    ## [1] A B
## Levels: A B
    fc2 <- parse_factor(c("C", "D"))
fc2
    ## [1] C D
## Levels: C D
    fct_c(fc1, fc2)
    ## [1] A B C D
## Levels: A B C D
    # Not the same as
c(fc1, fc2)
    ## [1] 1 2 1 2

  • fct_collapse(): combine multiple levels into one level.

    fc <- parse_factor(c("A", "B", "C", "A", "B", "C"))
fc
    ## [1] A B C A B C
## Levels: A B C
    fct_collapse(fc, "AB" = c("A", "B"))
    ## [1] AB AB C  AB AB C 
## Levels: AB C

  • fct_drop(): removes any levels that are unused.

    fc <- parse_factor(c("A", "B"), levels = c("A", "B", "C"))
fc
    ## [1] A B
## Levels: A B C
    fct_drop(fc)
    ## [1] A B
## Levels: A B

  • fct_expand(): adds one or more new levels.

    fc <- parse_factor(c("A", "B"))
fc
    ## [1] A B
## Levels: A B
    fct_expand(fc, "C", "Z")
    ## [1] A B
## Levels: A B C Z

  • fct_infreq(): Order by frequency of a level.

    fc <- parse_factor(c("A", "B", "C", "B", "C", "C"))
fct_count(fc)
    ## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   f         n
##   <fct> <int>
## 1 A         1
## 2 B         2
## 3 C         3
    fct_infreq(fc) 
    ## [1] A B C B C C
## Levels: C B A
    fct_infreq(fc) %>%
  fct_count()
    ## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   f         n
##   <fct> <int>
## 1 C         3
## 2 B         2
## 3 A         1
